{
  "enabled": true,
  "name": "3 · EOD: System Refresh",
  "version": "6.0.0",
  "description": "Autoresearch loop: maintenance → cascade to all organs → experiments (Karpathy-governed, protocol in heart.md).",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "Run the autoresearch loop. Protocol: ~/shared/context/body/heart.md. Read it first. heart.md is the source of truth for experiment protocol — do not override its parameters.\n\nCONTEXT LOAD (once):\n- ~/shared/context/body/heart.md (loop protocol — SOURCE OF TRUTH for experiments)\n- ~/shared/context/changelog.md (what changed last run)\n- ~/shared/context/active/current.md (live state)\n\n=== PHASE 1: MAINTENANCE ===\nRefresh ground truth from email/calendar.\n- Read changelog.md FIRST. Skip substeps where target was updated <24h ago AND no new signals reference it.\n- Update current.md: new projects, people, meetings, pending action statuses. Bump date.\n- Update org-chart.md if org changes detected.\n\nSLACK INGESTION (substep within Phase 1 — not a new phase):\n1. Load ~/shared/context/active/slack-channel-registry.json and ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json.\n2. Scan all Tier 1 channels: retrieve messages since last scan timestamp using batch_get_conversation_history. For threads with >5 replies, retrieve full thread via batch_get_thread_replies.\n3. Scan Tier 2 channels: only if scan_interval_hours has elapsed since last scan for that channel.\n4. Scan DM conversations with People Watch contacts (from channel registry people_watch section).\n5. Run Relevance Filter on all retrieved messages (same scoring model as morning routine — direct mention +100, manager +100, People Watch boosted +30, active project keyword +25, keyword trigger +20, Tier 1 channel +15, decision language +20, action assignment +25, deadline +15, escalation +20, hot topic +15, thread >5 replies +10; threshold: 25 points). Extract Signals from messages scoring >= 25.\n6. If signals found: produce ~/shared/context/intake/slack-digest-{YYYY-MM-DD-HHmm}.md (500 word cap, ranked by relevance score, [ACTION-RW] prefix for Richard's action items).\n7. Update ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json: last_scan timestamp, per-channel last_message_ts, signals_extracted counts, and tool_invocation_log entries for audit.\n8. On rate limit or API error: log the error to scan state, continue with other data sources. Do not fail the loop.\n9. RSW-CHANNEL INTAKE SCANNING (runs during rsw-channel scan in step 2 above):\n   - When scanning rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ), check each message's author_id:\n     • If author_id == U040ECP305S (Richard) AND message text does NOT start with any system_message_markers from rsw_channel_behavior config in slack-channel-registry.json (\"Daily Brief —\", \"System Dashboard\", \"📋\", \"🖥️\", \"[DRAFT for\"): this is an intake message from Richard's phone.\n       → Create ~/shared/context/intake/rsw-intake-{YYYYMMDD-HHmm}.md with content: message text, any links, timestamp.\n       → If message matches action_patterns from rsw_channel_behavior (\"remind me to\", \"follow up with\", \"todo:\", \"TODO\", \"need to\", \"don't forget\"): add [ACTION-RW] tag to the intake file.\n       → If message has file attachments: download via download_file_content and include content in the intake file.\n       → Intake file format:\n         # rsw-channel Intake — {date} {time} PT\n         Source: rsw-channel mobile drop\n         [ACTION-RW] (if action pattern matched)\n         {message text}\n         ---\n         Captured: {ISO timestamp}\n         Route: hands.md (if action item detected) or gut.md (general intake)\n     • If author_id != U040ECP305S: skip (not Richard's message).\n     • If message text starts with any system_message_markers: skip (system-posted message).\n10. CONVERSATION DATABASE WRITES (runs at end of Slack scan cycle):\n    After all messages have been retrieved and signals extracted, batch-write to DuckDB:\n    1. For ALL messages retrieved (not just relevant ones — the DB is the complete record):\n       INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_messages (ts, channel_id, channel_name, thread_ts, author_id, author_alias, author_name, text_preview, full_text, is_richard, is_thread_reply, reply_count, reaction_count, richard_reacted, relevance_score, signal_type)\n       VALUES (...)\n       - text_preview = first 200 characters of message text\n       - is_richard = TRUE when author_id = 'U040ECP305S'\n       - relevance_score and signal_type from the relevance filter (NULL for messages below threshold)\n    2. For threads with replies:\n       INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_threads (thread_ts, channel_id, channel_name, topic_summary, participant_aliases, message_count, decision_extracted, action_items, first_ts, last_ts)\n       - topic_summary: 1-2 sentence synthesis of thread topic\n       - participant_aliases: comma-separated list\n       - decision_extracted: extracted decision text if any, NULL otherwise\n       - action_items: extracted action items if any, NULL otherwise\n    3. For each unique author encountered:\n       INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_people (user_id, alias, display_name, first_interaction, last_interaction, total_messages, dm_messages, channel_messages, channels_shared, relationship_tier)\n       - On new author: set first_interaction = today, total_messages = count from this cycle\n       - On existing author: update last_interaction, increment message counts\n       - relationship_tier: sync from People Watch status (always_high, boosted, candidate, none)\n    4. Use batch operations — accumulate all rows during the scan, execute as a single DuckDB transaction via execute_query at the end. Target: <30 seconds added per cycle.\n    5. If DuckDB write fails: log error, continue. Existing organ routing is unaffected — DB writes are additive, not blocking.\n    6. For topic clusters detected by hot topic detection:\n       INSERT OR REPLACE INTO slack_topics (topic, \\\"week\\\", channel_count, message_count, participant_count, key_participants, status, related_project)\n       - week: current ISO week (e.g., '2026-W14')\n       - status: 'active' for new/continuing topics\n       - related_project: project name from current.md if applicable, NULL otherwise\nNote: The Slack digest in intake/ gets processed by the existing 'Process intake/ using gut.md Digestion Protocol' substep below — no separate processing needed.\n\n- Process intake/ using gut.md Digestion Protocol — extract facts into organs, archive processed files, delete transient files.\n- Review soul.md — suggest changes if role/preferences shifted (don't auto-edit).\n- Log all changes to changelog.md.\n\nDASHBOARD UPDATE (after Phase 1 maintenance completes):\nUpdate the live dashboard message in rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ) with fresh organ data.\n1. Read dashboard.message_ts from ~/shared/context/active/slack-scan-state.json — this is the message to edit.\n2. Compose fresh dashboard content in Slack mrkdwn using the 6-section format:\n   🖥️ *System Dashboard* — Updated {date} {time} PT\n   ━━━ *TODAY* ━━━ (from hands.md: top 3 priorities, pending count; calendar: meeting count)\n   ━━━ *STREAK* ━━━ (from amcc.md: streak counter, hard thing, days since last artifact)\n   ━━━ *MARKETS* ━━━ (from eyes.md: one-line status per market AU, MX, US, EU5, JP, CA)\n   ━━━ *HOT TOPICS* ━━━ (from slack-scan-state.json: hot_topics.active with channel count and participants)\n   ━━━ *WAITING ON RICHARD* ━━━ (from hands.md: pending responses with person and age)\n   ━━━ *FIVE LEVELS* ━━━ (from brain.md: current level positions and gate status)\n3. Edit the existing message using the Slack MCP (edit the message at message_ts in C0993SRL6FQ).\n4. After editing, mark rsw-channel as unread by calling batch_set_last_read with C0993SRL6FQ and a timestamp ONE TICK before the dashboard message_ts. Richard sees the updated dashboard as a notification.\n5. Update slack-scan-state.json → dashboard.last_updated with current timestamp.\n6. If edit fails: log error to slack-scan-state.json → last_scan.errors, continue. Dashboard stays stale until next successful update.\n\nFOCUS UPDATE (after dashboard update):\nPost a brief focus update to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ) listing any task changes from this cycle — new action items from Slack/email, completed items, escalated items. Keep under 150 words.\n1. Compare hands.md state before and after this maintenance cycle: identify new tasks added, tasks completed, items escalated or re-prioritized.\n2. If task changes exist, compose a focus update message (≤150 words, Slack mrkdwn format):\n   🔄 *Focus Update — {date} {time} PT*\n   *NEW* (new action items from Slack/email)\n   *DONE* (completed items)\n   *ESCALATED* (re-prioritized or escalated items)\n3. Post to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ) via post_message.\n4. After posting, mark rsw-channel as unread by calling batch_set_last_read with C0993SRL6FQ and a timestamp ONE TICK before the posted message's ts.\n5. If no task changes this cycle, skip the post.\n6. If post_message fails: log error to slack-scan-state.json → last_scan.errors, continue.\n\n=== ENRICHMENT PROCESSES (conditional — check cadence before running) ===\n\nENRICHMENT: WEEKLY RELATIONSHIP REFRESH (Fridays only):\nIF today is Friday:\n1. Query slack_people via DuckDB: SELECT alias, display_name, total_messages, last_interaction, relationship_tier FROM slack_people WHERE last_interaction >= current_date - INTERVAL 7 DAY ORDER BY total_messages DESC\n2. Promotion: any person NOT in People Watch with 3+ messages in trailing 7 days → add to slack-scan-state.json → people_watch_candidates\n3. Dormancy: any People Watch contact with last_interaction 60+ days ago → flag for demotion in scan state\n4. Update slack_people.relationship_tier values based on current People Watch status\n5. If changes detected (new candidates, dormant contacts, tier changes): produce brief delta summary → route to memory.md (respect word budget)\n6. If no changes: skip memory.md update\n7. Update slack-scan-state.json → enrichment_state.last_relationship_refresh with current timestamp\n\nENRICHMENT: WIKI PIPELINE CANDIDATES (weekly):\n1. Query slack_messages for threads where Richard gave detailed explanations:\n   - is_richard = TRUE AND length(full_text) > 200 AND is_thread_reply = TRUE\n   - Then check: did Richard send 3+ replies in the same thread_ts?\n   - Look for explanatory language: \"how to\", \"because\", \"the reason\", \"the way this works\", \"here's what\", \"step 1\"\n2. For each candidate thread: extract topic, Richard's explanation content, audience (who asked), thread link\n3. Deduplicate against existing ~/shared/context/wiki/demand-log.md entries — skip if already logged\n4. Check if a wiki article on the same topic already exists in ~/shared/artifacts/ — note overlap\n5. Append new candidates to ~/shared/context/wiki/demand-log.md with source attribution and one-sentence summary\n6. Update slack-scan-state.json → enrichment_state.last_wiki_pipeline_run with current timestamp\n\nENRICHMENT: PROACTIVE DRAFT SUGGESTIONS (every cycle):\n1. Query slack_messages for unanswered messages directed at Richard:\n   - author_id != 'U040ECP305S' (not Richard)\n   - AND (full_text contains 'prichwil' OR channel_id is a DM with Richard)\n   - AND richard_reacted = FALSE\n   - AND no reply from Richard in the same thread (check slack_messages for is_richard=TRUE with same thread_ts)\n   - AND message is 24+ hours old (ts < current_timestamp - INTERVAL 24 HOUR)\n2. For each unanswered message:\n   a. Load memory.md relationship graph tone notes for the sender\n   b. Load ~/shared/portable-body/voice/richard-style-slack.md if it exists for Slack register\n   c. Load thread context from slack_threads for the full conversation\n   d. Generate a draft response matching tone + register + thread context\n3. Post draft to rsw-channel (C0993SRL6FQ): \"[DRAFT for @{person} in #{channel}]: {draft text}\"\n4. Use create_draft via Slack MCP when available for the target channel, fall back to rsw-channel post\n5. After posting, mark rsw-channel as unread via batch_set_last_read (timestamp one tick before posted message ts)\n6. SKIP messages where Richard reacted with ANY emoji — a reaction IS a response per reaction_checking semantics\n\nENRICHMENT: MONTHLY SYNTHESIS (1st of month):\nIF today is the 1st of the month (or first system refresh of the month — check enrichment_state.last_monthly_synthesis):\n1. Query all 4 Slack tables for trailing 30 days\n2. Produce synthesis (≤500 words total across all organ updates):\n   - Topic trends: rising (new in slack_topics this month), falling (cooled), persistent\n   - New people: slack_people with first_interaction in last 30 days\n   - Channel activity shifts: message volume changes by channel\n   - Relationship graph changes: tier promotions, demotions, new candidates\n3. Route: strategic shifts → brain.md, relationship changes → memory.md, market context shifts → eyes.md\n4. Respect gut.md word budgets for each organ\n5. If a topic trended for 3+ weeks (appears in slack_topics for 3+ consecutive weeks): flag as wiki article candidate in demand-log.md\n6. TRIBAL KNOWLEDGE REFRESH (monthly, runs as part of this monthly synthesis):\n   a. Query slack_messages WHERE signal_type = 'question' AND ingested_at > current_date - INTERVAL 30 DAY — check what question-pattern messages were already captured from daily ingestion.\n   b. Search Slack for question patterns missed by daily ingestion: 'does anyone know', 'how do we', 'where is the', 'what\\'s the process for', 'who owns', 'where can I find', 'is there a doc', 'has anyone done' — with after:{30 days ago}, scoped to team channels.\n   c. INSERT OR REPLACE new question messages into slack_messages with signal_type = 'question'.\n   d. Cluster new questions with existing ~/shared/context/wiki/demand-log.md entries — update demand counts and recurrence data.\n   e. Flag any new high-demand topics (3+ occurrences in 30 days) in demand-log.md for wiki-editor prioritization.\n   f. Update slack-scan-state.json → enrichment_state.last_tribal_knowledge_refresh with current timestamp.\n7. Update slack-scan-state.json → enrichment_state.last_monthly_synthesis with current timestamp\n\nENRICHMENT: QUARTERLY STAKEHOLDER AUDIT (QBR-aligned):\nIF it has been 90+ days since enrichment_state.last_quarterly_audit (or last_quarterly_audit is null):\n1. Query slack_people + slack_messages for per-stakeholder data, trailing 90 days\n2. Key stakeholders: Kate Rundell, Brandon Munday, Lena Zak, Nick Georgijev (and any others in People Watch always_high_relevance)\n3. Per stakeholder produce: message volume (sent/received), avg response time, topics discussed, channel overlap, communication frequency trend\n4. Compare current quarter vs previous quarter (if data exists): flag response time increased >50%, message volume dropped >30%\n5. Calculate visibility gap metric: Richard's message volume and response patterns vs available peer data\n6. Route findings to nervous-system.md (Loop 9 data) and memory.md (relationship graph updates), respect word budgets\n7. Update slack-scan-state.json → enrichment_state.last_quarterly_audit with current timestamp\n\n=== PHASE 2: CASCADE TO ALL ORGANS ===\nPropagate Phase 1 changes. Read each organ, update only stale sections.\n- Eyes: refresh predicted QA (only topics with new signals). Update metrics/competitors if new data.\n- Memory: update relationship graph (only contacts in recent email). Update compressed context if projects changed. Do NOT update meeting briefs — those live in ~/shared/context/meetings/ now. If meetings/ series files have new open items that affect relationship context, update the relationship entry's 'Current topic' line only.\n- Hands: update action tracker (new tasks, completed, blockers, signals). Update overdue list.\n- Brain: add new decisions if made. Update Five Levels status if progress detected.\n- Spine: update system history if structural changes.\n- Nervous System: update delegation scorecard. Flag overdue calibration loops. On Fridays, generate weekly calibration report.\n- aMCC: update streak (did Richard do the hard thing since last run?). Rotate hard thing if previous one was completed or is now blocked. Update resistance taxonomy if new patterns observed.\n- Device: update delegation protocol statuses. Update tool factory if new automation opportunities surfaced.\n- Gut: AFTER all other organs updated, check each organ's word count against budget (see gut.md). Flag any over budget. Run bloat detection signals. Report gut health.\n- SKIP rule: if organ section updated <48h ago and upstream change is minor (single fact, not structural), skip.\n- ALWAYS cascade to Memory compressed context if current.md had structural changes.\n\nSLACK SIGNAL ROUTING (during Phase 2 cascade):\nWhen processing Slack digests from intake/, route each Signal to organs based on type:\n- decision → brain.md (decision log entry with source attribution) + current.md\n- action-item → hands.md (new action item with [Slack] source tag) + current.md (pending actions)\n- status-change → current.md (updated project status line) + eyes.md (if metric-related). ALSO: if the status-change contains launch/dial/migration/test/pause language ('launched', 'live', 'dialed up', 'migrated', 'paused', 'weblab', 'test started', 'test ended'), INSERT INTO change_log (id, market, date, category, description, source) with source='slack' and auto-increment id. Deduplicate against existing change_log rows (same market + date + similar description = skip). Additionally, if the status-change contains experiment/test language ('weblab', 'A/B', 'test', 'experiment', 'results show', 'lift of'), check if an experiments row exists for that test name: if yes, UPDATE status/end_date/result/effect_size/decision as new data arrives; if no, INSERT a new row with available fields and status='active'.\n- escalation → current.md (escalation note on relevant project) + hands.md (if Richard needs to act)\n- mention → current.md (context note, only if substantive)\n- topic-update → current.md (hot topic summary) + brain.md (if strategic)\n- Relationship info (tone shift, new person) → memory.md (updated relationship graph entry)\n- Market metrics / competitive intel → eyes.md (updated metrics or competitor note)\nConstraints:\n- No new organ files created — all Slack signals absorbed into existing organs.\n- Before writing Slack-sourced content to an organ, check its word budget in gut.md. If at capacity, compress existing content first or defer the signal to the next cycle.\n- Source attribution: every Slack-sourced fact written to an organ MUST include [Slack: #channel, author, date] tag for provenance.\n- After routing all signals from a digest, delete the processed digest file from intake/.\n\nVOLUME CONTROL & HOT TOPIC DETECTION (applies during Phase 1 ingestion and Phase 2 cascade):\nWeekly cumulative tracking:\n- After each organ write from Slack-sourced content, update volume_tracking.words_by_organ in slack-scan-state.json.\n- Week resets on Monday (aligned with week_start field).\n20% ceiling rule:\n- If cumulative Slack-sourced words for any organ exceed 20% of that organ's word budget (per gut.md) in a single week, reduce scan frequency for channels feeding that organ: Tier 1 channels scan every other cycle, Tier 2 channels skip until next week.\n- Log the throttle in scan state. Resume normal frequency on weekly reset.\n- Budget reference: Memory 3500w (700w ceiling), Brain 2500w (500w), Eyes 2500w (500w), Hands 2000w (400w), current.md flag if >500w/week.\nHot topic detection:\n- When the same topic appears in Signals from 3+ distinct channels within a 24-hour window, flag as hot topic in slack-scan-state.json hot_topics.active (with topic name, first_seen, channels list, key_participants, signal_count).\n- Include hot topic summary in the Slack Digest. Boost relevance score +15 for all messages in the topic cluster (+25 if topic relates to an active project in current.md).\nHot topic cooling:\n- If a hot topic has no new Signals for 48 hours, move from hot_topics.active to hot_topics.cooled. Stop applying relevance boost. Remove from digest hot topics section.\nPeople Watch derivation:\n- During Phase 2 cascade, after memory.md is updated, re-derive the people_watch section in slack-channel-registry.json from memory.md's Relationship Graph.\n- always_high_relevance: Richard's direct manager (Brandon). boosted: all Relationship Graph entries with interaction in last 60 days. Dormant contacts (60+ days): excluded until they resurface.\n- Record last_derived timestamp in the channel registry.\nNew person detection:\n- Track unique Slack users in conversations with Richard (DMs or @mentions). If a user not in People Watch appears 3+ times in a 7-day window, add to people_watch_candidates in scan state.\nDM monitoring:\n- Scan Richard's DM conversations with People Watch contacts. Extract signals using the same Relevance Filter. Respect read-only guardrails (see slack-guardrails.md).\n\n=== GATE: EXPERIMENT DECISION ===\n- ALWAYS run Phase 3 — experiments are generated at runtime, there is no queue to be empty.\n- Karpathy's per-organ cooldown (heart.md) excludes organs modified by maintenance in this invocation.\n\n=== PHASE 3: EXPERIMENTS (Karpathy-governed — heart.md is source of truth) ===\nExperiments are governed by the Karpathy agent. The FULL experiment protocol lives in heart.md Steps 1-6. DO NOT duplicate or override any parameters here.\n\nRead heart.md and execute exactly as written. Key points (for reference only — heart.md governs):\n- Target selection uses Bayesian priors from DuckDB autoresearch_priors table (UCB-weighted)\n- A/B/C blind eval: Agent A (modified+context), Agent B (original+context, control), Agent C (modified+zero context, portability)\n- Keep/revert based on delta_ab (did the change improve or degrade?), not static thresholds\n- No hard cap on experiments per batch — run until 3 consecutive reverts\n- Log each experiment to DuckDB autoresearch_experiments table AND changelog.md\n- Update Bayesian priors after each decision\n- SNAPSHOT before every edit. Restore from .bak on REVERT.\n- Word budgets (gut.md) still enforced as ceilings.\n\n=== PHASE 4: SUGGESTED CHANGES ===\nPresent up to 3 suggestions to Richard. Each suggestion MUST:\n- Connect to a specific goal in brain.md (Five Levels) or a calibration finding in nervous-system.md\n- Be measurable (what metric improves, by how much, over what timeframe)\n- Be reversible (can be undone if it doesn't work)\n- NOT modify soul.md or steering files without Richard's explicit approval\n- NOT restructure organs (that's a deliberate architecture decision, not a suggestion)\n\nFormat:\n1. [TITLE] — [description]. Why: [goal/calibration connection]. Measure: [what metric, target, timeframe]. Reversible: [how to undo]. Risk: [what could go wrong]. → Approve/Deny?\n\nIf fewer than 3 suggestions meet these criteria, present fewer. Quality over quantity.\n\n=== PHASE 5: CONCLUSION ===\n1-2 sentences: what changed, expected impact, forward look.\n\n=== REPORT ===\n1. Maintenance: what changed\n2. Cascade: which organs updated (list all 11), gut health (word counts, bloat signals)\n3. aMCC: streak update, hard thing status\n4. Experiment: which ran (or why skipped), ADVANCE/RESET/SKIPPED, word count delta, accuracy scores\n5. Suggestions: what was proposed (or why fewer than 3)\n6. Next run: next experiment in queue, organs approaching staleness, calibration loops due\n\n=== SELF-AUDIT (run last, every time) ===\nBefore logging to changelog, verify:\n1. CASCADE COMPLETENESS: List every organ in the body (brain, eyes, hands, memory, spine, nervous-system, amcc, device, gut). For each: was it checked during Phase 2? If skipped, was the skip rule applied correctly (updated <48h + minor change)? If an organ was neither updated nor explicitly skipped, flag it as a MISSED CASCADE.\n2. STRUCTURAL CHANGE CHECK: Did this run create, rename, move, or delete any file? If yes, run the Structural Change Protocol from nervous-system.md — check that body.md, soul.md, spine.md, heart.md, and all hooks were updated.\n3. COHERENCE SPOT-CHECK: Pick 2 random cross-references from the files you touched (e.g., a path in soul.md, a hook cascade target). Verify they point to files that exist and contain what they claim. If any are broken, fix immediately.\n\nLog self-audit results in the report. Format:\nSELF-AUDIT: Cascade [X]/9 organs covered. Structural changes: [yes/no]. Coherence spot-check: [X]/2 valid.\n\nLog to ~/shared/context/changelog.md.\n\n=== PHASE 6: HOUSEKEEPING & GIT SYNC ===\nBefore pushing, deduplicate the MCP autoApprove lists in ~/.kiro/settings/mcp.json. Run: python3 -c \"import json; f='$HOME/.kiro/settings/mcp.json'; d=json.load(open(f)); [srv.__setitem__('autoApprove', list(dict.fromkeys(srv.get('autoApprove',[])))) for srv in d.get('mcpServers',{}).values()]; json.dump(d, open(f,'w'), indent=2)\"\nThen run: ~/shared/tools/git-sync/sync.sh push\nThis pushes all changes to the personal GitHub repo so the local machine stays in sync. Silent if nothing changed. Do not skip this step."
  }
}
